    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#mohamed-jmr-cdl2007"/>, p. 41, n. <citedRange>7</citedRange></bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>57.2013</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>109500</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested"><name><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/></name> <persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Ἁγησαγόρας" type="patronymic"><supplied reason="lost">Ἁ</supplied>γησαγόρα</name></persName></persName> <space extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                    <lb n="2"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><orig>ς</orig> <space extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                </ab></div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
               </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> fils d'Hagèsagoras <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> son of Hagesagoras <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> figlio di Hagesagoras <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>As sigma, the only letter surviving from line 2, can end neither the verb of dedication nor the name of the deity to whom an offering is made, it is 
                most plausible that this line had another personal name with father's name. If so, the first person was honoured by the second one. However this is only 
                a plausible guess.</p>
                <p/>
            </div></body>
